We can “back‐solve” the balance by (a) “starting” with the initial “investment” entry (the three “Initial20231231001” records whose amounts add to 13,000,000) and then “adjust” that “balance” by adding the net effect of all “transactions” that (directly or indirectly) alter equity or add items to your “Accounts Payable” (that is, unpaid “Purchase” entries) – roughly, you add “profits” from “Sales” (after subtracting attendant expenses) and add any “Purchases” marked “Unpaid” which represent a liability increase. (Other “internal” transfers–for example, a “Cash to bank transfer” or a paid purchase which converts cash into inventory or fixed‐assets–do not affect total Liabilities and Owner’s Equity.)

In our working the sum is computed step–by–step. (The reader will note that after starting with 13,000,000 the running “total” was adjusted by each “expense” (which reduces owner’s equity) and each “sale” (whose “profit” — that is the “after tax amount” less the “cost amount”– is added) and by “Purchase” records that “remain Unpaid” (which add to the liabilities).) After processing every record in sequence the final “total” comes to about 14,199,093.43.

Thus, in summary we have:

• Total Liabilities and Owners Equity (Initial Value) = 13,000,000.00 
• Total Liabilities and Owners Equity (End Value) ≈ 14,199,093.43
